Tree (Hierarchical Structure) 🌳
🧠 Logic:A Tree is a non-linear, hierarchical data structure that organizes data elements (called Nodes) in a structured way. Unlike linear structures (arrays, lists, stacks, queues), elements in a tree are connected in a parent-child relationship.Key terms:Root: The topmost node in the tree (has no parent).Child: A node connected to another node one level below.Leaf: A node with no children.Edge: The link connecting one node to another.A Binary Tree is a specific type where each node has at most two children (left and right).📌 Example:Java// Conceptual Node Structure
class TreeNode {
    int data;
    TreeNode left;  // Reference to the left child
    TreeNode right; // Reference to the right child
}

// Tree Structure:
//         (Root)
//          10
//         /  \
//      (Left)  (Right)
//       5      15
🔤 Java Code (Basic Node and Creation):Javaclass BinaryTreeNode {
    int data;
    BinaryTreeNode left;
    BinaryTreeNode right;

    BinaryTreeNode(int data) {
        this.data = data;
    }
}

public class TreeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Creating the root
        BinaryTreeNode root = new BinaryTreeNode(10);
        
        // Connecting children
        root.left = new BinaryTreeNode(5);
        root.right = new BinaryTreeNode(15);
        
        // Further connecting a grandchild
        root.left.right = new BinaryTreeNode(7);
        
        System.out.println("Root Data: " + root.data);     // Output: 10
        System.out.println("Left Child Data: " + root.left.data); // Output: 5
        System.out.println("Grandchild Data: " + root.left.right.data); // Output: 7
    }
}
🧾 Notebook Points:Java📘 Tree:
→ Non-linear, Hierarchical data structure
→ Root: Top node (no parent)
→ Leaf: Node with no children

🔢 Binary Tree: Each node has max 2 children (left, right)
✅ Summary Table:🏗️ Structure💡 Principle🛠️ Insertion/RemovalQueueFIFO (First-In, First-Out)Rear (Insert), Front (Remove)TreeHierarchical (Parent-Child)Complex, depends on Tree type (e.g., BST rules)
